## BIG Announcement for the Future of Folding

Hello Folding! We as a subnet are coming to an inflection point. We have spent the last 4 months learning, developing, and refining this subnet for molecular biology research, and the results have been incredibly fruitful. Hats off to the incredible community we have here! 🚀

### GROMACS to OpenMM
During this process, various complications and desires have led us to the point we are today. Starting this sprint, we are accelerating towards a complete refactor of the SN25 codebase. In particular, we are moving AWAY from GROMACS to an open-source alternative called OpenMM (https://openmm.org). Below, we enumerate the key factors that are motivating us to this body of work:

1. GROMACS is non-Pythonic, which has led us to a considerable amount of tech debt that needs to be resolved if this product is to go live. OpenMM is Pythonic by design, has better error handling, and will simplify our pipelines.
2. GROMACS simulations are not reproducible when using GPUs. Reproducibility is a key pillar of scientific research, and the lack of reproducibility hinders the scale of this product. The only way to ensure direct reproducibility in GROMACS is to collapse the compute space to a single-core CPU machine, which, of course, does not scale with the type of work we need to do. OpenMM gives us much stronger reproducibility guarantees, allowing us not only to give researchers what they need but also to enforce hyperparameters for the simulation depending on what is desired by users.

Therefore, you will start to see branches that are focused on development towards OpenMM. We encourage the community to read some of the introductory resources (http://docs.openmm.org/8.0.0/userguide/index.html). Furthermore, we WILL be supporting this transition with a 2-week minimum testnet development cycle for our miners.

### Frontends
Alongside the changes to our backend, we are continuing to develop the frontend product for SN25, alongside a new and improved dashboard. Keep your eyes peeled!

If there are any questions regarding this transition, please reach out here or in DMs!

# OpenMM Testnet Release Announcement! 🚀 🧬 

Macrocosmos is SUPER excited to announce that we are now supporting an official release of OpenMM on Testnet 141! This is the first major milestone to get the community involved in our push towards a better, more diverse, and more reliable simulation backend. There are many aspects of the validation pipeline that have changed since gromacs, and I would like to highlight the most important one: 

## **Reproducibility and Control**
While operating with Gromacs, there is no way for us to enforce if a miner should run one configuration over another, even if a validator asks for it. This opens up the box for alterations to the config in unintended ways, and we want future users of the product to have control over this aspect. 

Therefore, the major change in the validation pipeline looks at reproducing **miner** simulations given the **original** config validators sent over the wire. Since we have some reproducibility guarantees, the agreement of the validator re-run simulation and the submitted results is key here. This gives us much stronger control over what we want miners to run. 

## Key Thoughts 
The complexity of this space is absolutely massive, and there are going to be things we cannot see during our testing that we will only see on testnet. For this reason, we are committed to supporting at least 3 validators on testnet for this release by 16h from now. This will give the community sufficient sampling to try out the new system. 

**WARNING:** The branch is sill very much in development, and we need your help. Any issues, bugs, edge cases, etc.. that you see, please please post them here! We will be gathering all the feedback from the community as fast as possible to bring openmm to mainnet. 

The testnet branch is here: https://github.com/macrocosm-os/folding/tree/openmm

The dynamic of Openmm is much different than to Gromacs, so I urge miners that want to stay on top to get involved sooner rather than later 🙂

Working with a bunch of the recent logged data on wandb with a `version tag >= 0.3.0`, I put together this distribution. Each colour is a *relative* epsilon amount, where anything **above** the y = x line is where the relative percentage improvement results in an energy that must be **larger** than the current epsilon requirement.
